---
import MoatVisualization from '../../components/MoatVisualization.jsx';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <meta
      name="description"
      content="A structured visualization of alternative-data underwriting moat decay across four Actions Capital portfolio companies — Kueski, Tpaga, Yassir, and Vammo."
    />
    <title>Alternative-data moats are decaying assets — Aditya Bhosale</title>
    <link
      rel="preconnect"
      href="https://fonts.googleapis.com"
    />
    <link
      rel="preconnect"
      href="https://fonts.gstatic.com"
      crossorigin
    />
    <link
      href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=EB+Garamond:ital,wght@0,400;0,500;0,600;1,400&display=swap"
      rel="stylesheet"
    />
    <style>
      :root {
        --color-text: #111827;
        --color-text-muted: #4b5563;
        --color-text-faint: #6b7280;
        --color-border: #e5e7eb;
        --color-accent: #1d4ed8;
        --max-content: 720px;
        --max-viz: 1000px;
      }

      * {
        box-sizing: border-box;
      }

      body {
        margin: 0;
        font-family: 'EB Garamond', Georgia, serif;
        color: var(--color-text);
        background: #ffffff;
        font-size: 18px;
        line-height: 1.6;
        -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;
      }

      .page {
        max-width: var(--max-viz);
        margin: 0 auto;
        padding: 48px 24px 96px;
      }

      .breadcrumb {
        font-size: 14px;
        color: var(--color-text-faint);
        margin-bottom: 24px;
      }

      .breadcrumb a {
        color: var(--color-text-faint);
        text-decoration: none;
      }

      .breadcrumb a:hover {
        color: var(--color-text);
        text-decoration: underline;
      }

      .article-header {
        max-width: var(--max-content);
        margin-bottom: 32px;
      }

      h1 {
        font-size: 36px;
        font-weight: 600;
        line-height: 1.2;
        margin: 0 0 12px;
        letter-spacing: -0.01em;
      }

      .subtitle {
        font-size: 18px;
        color: var(--color-text-muted);
        font-style: italic;
        margin-bottom: 8px;
      }

      .meta {
        font-size: 14px;
        color: var(--color-text-faint);
      }

      .article-body {
        max-width: var(--max-content);
        margin: 0 auto 48px 0;
      }

      .article-body p {
        margin: 0 0 18px;
      }

      .article-body strong {
        font-weight: 600;
      }

      .article-body em {
        font-style: italic;
      }

      .article-body a {
        color: var(--color-accent);
        text-decoration: underline;
        text-decoration-thickness: 1px;
        text-underline-offset: 2px;
      }

      .lead {
        font-size: 20px;
        line-height: 1.5;
        color: var(--color-text);
        margin-bottom: 24px;
      }

      h2 {
        font-size: 24px;
        font-weight: 600;
        margin: 40px 0 16px;
        letter-spacing: -0.005em;
      }

      .viz-section {
        margin: 48px 0;
      }

      .viz-section-header {
        max-width: var(--max-content);
        margin-bottom: 24px;
      }

      .limitations {
        max-width: var(--max-content);
        margin-top: 48px;
        padding: 24px;
        background-color: #f9fafb;
        border-left: 3px solid #d1d5db;
        border-radius: 0 4px 4px 0;
      }

      .limitations h3 {
        font-size: 16px;
        font-weight: 600;
        margin: 0 0 12px;
        color: var(--color-text);
        text-transform: uppercase;
        letter-spacing: 0.05em;
      }

      .limitations p {
        font-size: 16px;
        color: var(--color-text-muted);
        margin: 0 0 12px;
        line-height: 1.55;
      }

      .limitations p:last-child {
        margin-bottom: 0;
      }

      .footer {
        max-width: var(--max-content);
        margin-top: 64px;
        padding-top: 24px;
        border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border);
        font-size: 14px;
        color: var(--color-text-faint);
      }

      .footer a {
        color: var(--color-text-faint);
        text-decoration: underline;
      }

      @media (max-width: 640px) {
        body {
          font-size: 17px;
        }
        h1 {
          font-size: 28px;
        }
        h2 {
          font-size: 22px;
        }
        .lead {
          font-size: 18px;
        }
        .page {
          padding: 32px 20px 64px;
        }
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="page">
      <div class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">aditya bhosale</a> / <a href="/analyses">analyses</a> / alternative-data moat decay
      </div>

      <header class="article-header">
        <h1>Alternative-data moats are decaying assets</h1>
        <div class="subtitle">
          Visualizing competitive-moat decay across four Actions Capital portfolio companies
        </div>
        <div class="meta">May 2026</div>
      </header>

      <div class="article-body">
        <p class="lead">
          The key question for emerging-markets-focused consumer fintech & industrials companies over the next ~2 years isn't which companies have the strongest alternative-data underwriting capabilities (most established players have converged on broadly similar capabilities), but how quickly those capabilities will erode in dominance as regulatory standardization and third-party data infrastructure mature, leading to commodization of alternative-data.

        </p>

        <p>
          I bulit the model below to visualize the effect of that commoditization on alternative-data based moats across four relevant PortCos (clustered) – <strong>Kueski</strong> (Mexico, BNPL and consumer credit), <strong>Tpaga</strong> (Colombia, payments wallet, recently 30% acquired by Banco Serfinanza), <strong>Yassir</strong> (North Africa, super-app, generalist use-cases), and <strong>Vammo</strong> (brazil, electric mobility financing). Each company's competitive moat is decomposed into a couple underlying components – data-access advantages, infrastructure positions, regulatory licenses, partnership channels. Each component is assigned a starting weight (its current contribution to the overall moat) and a transition function tied to specific exogenous catalysts: open finance rollout dates, emergence of third-party data aggregators, entry of incumbent operators, & operationalization of strategic partnerships.

        </p>

        <p>
          The four scenario inputs below the chart were built to stress-test the moat dynamics. Three of these input functions are negative catalysts (advancing the timing of regulatory rollouts; third-party aggregator entries; incumbent competitive launches). The remaning (earlier completion of Algeria's fintech licensing framework) is actually counterintuitive, as it <em>reduces Yassir's moat</em>, because regulatory standardization makes the licensing process accessible to new entrants who currently face the same multi-year ambiguity Yassir has already navigated. Two components grow rather than decay: Tpaga's Banco Serfinanza partnership operationalizes over roughly 12 months from the March 2026 deal close, and Vammo's Manaus manufacturing investment scales over the next ~2 years from initial deployment.

        </p>

        <p>
          The core observation from the model is that alternative-data underwriting has shifted from moat to baseline, and the next ~2 years of value creation will come from components other than underwriting capability. The visualization shows how sensitive this conclusion is to the timing of specific catalysts, which are non-exhaustive here.

        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- The interactive visualization (React island) -->
      <div class="viz-section">
        <div class="viz-section-header">
          <h2>Moat decay curves under scenario inputs</h2>
        </div>
        <MoatVisualization client:load />
      </div>

      <!-- The "what this is not" section — the most important part for credibility -->
      <div class="limitations">
        <h3>Limitations</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>This is not a valuation tool.</strong> The weights and transition parameters
          are defensible starting estimates, but can't be treated as predictions. The framework is more useful than any specific output.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>This cannot capture interaction effects between scenarios.</strong>
          i.e. What happens to Kueski if Mexico open finance and a major incumbent launch occur
          simultaneously? This type of scenarios isn't modeled — the components compound in the visualization but
          are treated as independent in the underlying math.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Each portco's starting moat at t=0 is normalized to its stated baseline.</strong>
          The y-axis represents relative change from that baseline as catalysts occur, not
          absolute moat "levels". The numbers are internally consistent
          but not externally comparable to other moat-measurement frameworks. I realized this while doing independent research on related frameworks on moat decay.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>The model excludes verticals where I lack an independent view.</strong>
          Tpaga's claimed "agentic AI for financial services" product, for example, has a
          weight = 0 because I can't verify the claim. If it becomes a real
          product at scale, that's an upside scenario this model does not currently capture.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="footer">
        <p>
          The paper on Actions' emerging-market financial services / industrials portfolio
          <span style="color: var(--color-text-faint);">(on Substack)</span>
          discusses my broader thesis. Parameter documentation
          and source code is on
          <a href="https://github.com/adityanbhosale/personal-page" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            GitHub for reference
          </a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
